\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2775584 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6423686\charrsid7763791 At the end of the 1914-'18 war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7343200 OB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6423686\charrsid7763791 
Yes. Yes. His father - was in the first war and - he suffered from - he - he - he suffered from T.B. when he came home, which he had contracted while he was in the Army. And - his wife }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1074794\charrsid7763791 nursed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6423686\charrsid7763791  him, they lived in Stoke, and she caught it from him, and -
 they had two boys. One was - just a young baby, about ten months old, and the other one would be about - two. So - they both died within a few months of each other and they were both twenty-six years of age. So - the grandmother had the elder boy and I h
ad the baby boy. And of course he grew up like a brother, just like a brother he was to the two - to the girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2775584 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6423686\charrsid7763791 Did you in fact adopt him?
